00:01:13,940 --> 00:01:16,100
I've lived in the
theatre since I was a kid.

2
00:01:16,260 --> 00:01:17,900
What I don't know about acting

3
00:01:18,100 --> 00:01:18,660
isn't worth knowing.

4
00:01:18,860 --> 00:01:21,100
Now, you may be 20 years
old and just beginning,

5
00:01:21,940 --> 00:01:23,740
but I think you're a genius.

6
00:01:24,100 --> 00:01:26,460
You've got magnetism,
but no idea how to use it.

7
00:01:26,860 --> 00:01:29,020
You have to grab the audience
by the throat and say:

8
00:01:29,620 --> 00:01:31,660
"Now, you buggers, you
pay attention to me!"

9
00:01:34,620 --> 00:01:36,180
and remember this,

10
00:01:36,660 --> 00:01:38,540
when you're on the stage acting,

11
00:01:39,300 --> 00:01:40,940
the theatre is the only reality.

12
00:01:43,340 --> 00:01:44,580
Everything else, the world outside,

13
00:01:44,780 --> 00:01:46,940
what civilians call the real world,

14
00:01:47,940 --> 00:01:49,100
is nothing but fantasy.

15
00:01:49,300 --> 00:01:51,460
And I bloody well
won't let you forget it.

16
00:01:53,180 --> 00:01:55,420
The trouble is, darling,
I'm an incurable romantic.

17
00:01:59,540 --> 00:02:01,020
I believe in love,

18
00:02:02,100 --> 00:02:03,700
I believe in happiness,

19
00:02:04,660 --> 00:02:05,260
I believe in us.

20
00:02:05,260 --> 00:02:07,860
(Archie) No, you don't.
You're just saying that.

21
00:02:09,900 --> 00:02:11,900
There's someone else, isn't there?

22
00:02:12,780 --> 00:02:14,300
I love you, I do.

23
00:02:15,980 --> 00:02:17,460
I do, I
love you--

24
00:02:17,820 --> 00:02:18,820
and I used to believe

25
00:02:18,980 --> 00:02:20,700
we'd live happily ever after.

26
00:02:22,220 --> 00:02:23,180
Didn't you?

27
00:02:23,380 --> 00:02:25,180
With every fiber of my being.

28
00:02:27,140 --> 00:02:28,540
only now...

29
00:02:29,460 --> 00:02:31,020
[Audience applauding]

30
00:03:12,420 --> 00:03:13,860
[Car honking]

31
00:03:14,460 --> 00:03:16,100
[Clock bell tolls]

32
00:03:17,300 --> 00:03:18,220
[Door squeaking]

33
00:03:18,380 --> 00:03:20,140
Good morning, miss Lambert.

34
00:03:20,340 --> 00:03:20,940
Good morning, Margery,

35
00:03:21,060 --> 00:03:23,180
is anyone with my lord and master?

36
00:03:23,780 --> 00:03:25,380
(Margery) No.

37
00:03:26,420 --> 00:03:28,420
Darling, what are you doing here?

38
00:03:29,060 --> 00:03:30,100
I want an answer, Michael.

39
00:03:30,300 --> 00:03:31,700
What's the question?

40
00:03:31,900 --> 00:03:32,460
What did I say to you

41
00:03:32,660 --> 00:03:34,620
before we went to sleep last night, hmm?

42
00:03:38,540 --> 00:03:40,060
Uh, I give up. What did you say to me

43
00:03:40,260 --> 00:03:41,860
before we went to sleep last night?

44
00:03:42,060 --> 00:03:42,900
I said I was tired.

45
00:03:43,100 --> 00:03:45,420
It seems a perfectly natural thing
to say before you go to sleep.

46
00:03:45,780 --> 00:03:48,060
Christ, Michael, you can be
an irritating little shit!

47
00:03:48,580 --> 00:03:50,220
Julia, Julia, really,

48
00:03:50,460 --> 00:03:52,540
if your public could
only hear your language.

49
00:03:52,900 --> 00:03:53,740
I want them to hear.

50
00:03:53,900 --> 00:03:55,580
I want every bloody one of them to hear.

51
00:03:55,780 --> 00:03:57,540
I'm tired. I am utterly exhausted.

52
00:03:57,780 --> 00:03:59,340
I need a holiday.

53
00:03:59,900 --> 00:04:00,780
Just admit it, Michael.

54
00:04:00,980 --> 00:04:02,940
you've never understood what it means

55
00:04:03,300 --> 00:04:04,220
to carry a play,

56
00:04:04,420 --> 00:04:05,260
to sweat it out night after night.

57
00:04:05,460 --> 00:04:07,940
I'm the only one who takes it
seriously, Michael, you know that.

58
00:04:08,420 --> 00:04:10,900
All you do is count the money and
think it's a bloody great lark.

59
00:04:12,180 --> 00:04:13,060
Take the play off.

60
00:04:13,260 --> 00:04:14,940
But we'll lose a fortune.

61
00:04:15,860 --> 00:04:17,060
Our partner won't like it.

62
00:04:17,260 --> 00:04:18,900
To hell with dolly!

63
00:04:23,620 --> 00:04:24,700
[Sighing]

64
00:04:24,900 --> 00:04:26,340
I'm sorry, sweetheart.

65
00:04:26,540 --> 00:04:28,380
God, I didn't mean to be so vile.

66
00:04:28,580 --> 00:04:30,620
It's just I'm-- I'm
near to breaking point.

67
00:04:32,580 --> 00:04:34,300
Everything's so tedious.

68
00:04:34,940 --> 00:04:36,100
[Sighing]

69
00:04:36,300 --> 00:04:37,980
I want something to happen.

70
00:04:38,660 --> 00:04:39,900
What?

71
00:04:40,340 --> 00:04:41,660
I wish I knew.

72
00:04:41,820 --> 00:04:44,020
Please. please close the
play at the end of the month.

73
00:04:47,420 --> 00:04:48,020
[Exhales]

74
00:04:48,180 --> 00:04:49,900
Yeah. I really do
have to think about it.

75
00:04:50,100 --> 00:04:52,100
We can't have the theatre dark.

76
00:04:53,740 --> 00:04:54,300
Hmm?

77
00:04:54,380 --> 00:04:56,540
I'll try and see what
I can do. I promise.

78
00:04:57,260 --> 00:04:58,540
Hmm?

79
00:04:58,740 --> 00:04:59,780
Please.

80
00:04:59,980 --> 00:05:01,060
I promise.

81
00:05:01,220 --> 00:05:02,620
Thank you.

82
00:05:03,660 --> 00:05:04,340
You were very quiet

83
00:05:04,540 --> 00:05:05,900
leaving the house this morning.

84
00:05:06,100 --> 00:05:07,180
Well, I didn't want to wake you.

85
00:05:07,380 --> 00:05:08,260
You were dead to the world.

86
00:05:08,460 --> 00:05:10,620
Hmm. I did my exercises
and went for a run.

87
00:05:10,940 --> 00:05:12,540
Exercises, running...

88
00:05:12,940 --> 00:05:13,500
God, Michael,

89
00:05:13,580 --> 00:05:15,420
you're the vainest man in London.

90
00:05:15,700 --> 00:05:17,180
Me, vain? nonsense.

91
00:05:17,500 --> 00:05:18,060
[Giggles]

92
00:05:18,060 --> 00:05:20,900
I just want to preserve my magnificent
good looks for as long as possible.

93
00:05:21,820 --> 00:05:23,220
[Chuckling]

94
00:05:24,180 --> 00:05:25,140
Oh, yes, speaking of good looks,

95
00:05:25,340 --> 00:05:27,500
did you notice that
young man as you came in?

96
00:05:28,180 --> 00:05:28,980
No.

97
00:05:29,180 --> 00:05:30,020
He's an American.

98
00:05:30,220 --> 00:05:32,340
Son of a friend of a
friend of Eddie Gilbert's.

99
00:05:32,860 --> 00:05:34,980
I can't see what that's
got to do with me.

100
00:05:35,220 --> 00:05:36,860
He admires you tremendously.

101
00:05:37,060 --> 00:05:39,260
Oh, he sounds frightfully intelligent.

102
00:05:40,020 --> 00:05:41,420
What's his name?

103
00:05:41,860 --> 00:05:43,340
Can't remember.

104
00:05:43,540 --> 00:05:44,420
Uh, unfortunately,

105
00:05:44,620 --> 00:05:46,260
he's as poor as a church mouse.

106
00:05:46,420 --> 00:05:48,620
I thought we might give
him a spot of lunch.

107
00:05:49,020 --> 00:05:51,300
Well, he's awfully
good-mannered, for an American.

108
00:05:52,380 --> 00:05:53,780
(Julia) uh!

109
00:05:55,860 --> 00:05:56,860
Rubbish mail, Margery.

110
00:05:57,060 --> 00:05:57,620
Yes, Mr. Gosselyn.

111
00:05:57,660 --> 00:05:59,860
Uh, I would like to
introduce you to my wife,

112
00:06:00,300 --> 00:06:00,900
Julia Lambert.

113
00:06:00,980 --> 00:06:02,340
Julia, this
is-- this is--

114
00:06:02,540 --> 00:06:04,900
this is the young man
I was telling you about.

115
00:06:05,140 --> 00:06:06,020
He wants to learn the business,

116
00:06:06,220 --> 00:06:08,300
so we're starting him
off with our accountant.

117
00:06:08,500 --> 00:06:10,500
It-it's an honor to
meet you, miss Lambert.

118
00:06:10,780 --> 00:06:12,220
I wonder if we could persuade you

119
00:06:12,380 --> 00:06:14,140
to come and eat a chop with us.

120
00:06:14,300 --> 00:06:16,300
Michael will drive you back after lunch.

121
00:06:17,420 --> 00:06:18,780
Gee, that's real kind of you.

122
00:06:18,980 --> 00:06:21,020
You two take the lift,
I'll take the stairs.

123
00:06:21,540 --> 00:06:23,060
Last one down's a sissy.

124
00:06:23,580 --> 00:06:25,020
Miss Lambert,

125
00:06:27,020 --> 00:06:28,300
could I-- could
I ask you a favor?

126
00:06:28,500 --> 00:06:31,220
I can't give you any more
room, if that's what you mean.

127
00:06:31,620 --> 00:06:33,540
No, no, no, it's, uh... I wonder...

128
00:06:34,220 --> 00:06:34,820
would you...

129
00:06:34,820 --> 00:06:36,740
would you let me have a photograph?

130
00:06:36,940 --> 00:06:37,580
Of course.

131
00:06:37,780 --> 00:06:38,540
Gee, that's swell of you.

132
00:06:38,740 --> 00:06:40,860
I've seen you in
"Farewell, my love" 3 times.

133
00:06:41,180 --> 00:06:42,940
You haven't. Have you really?

134
00:06:43,100 --> 00:06:44,220
It's such a silly play.

135
00:06:44,420 --> 00:06:45,100
Oh, it's not the play,

136
00:06:45,300 --> 00:06:47,220
it's you. You're just... just great.

137
00:06:48,620 --> 00:06:49,500
I'm glad you liked me.

138
00:06:49,700 --> 00:06:50,860
Liked you? I loved you.

139
00:06:51,060 --> 00:06:52,180
[Elevator thudding]

140
00:06:52,340 --> 00:06:52,940
[Door squeaking]

141
00:06:53,100 --> 00:06:54,580
- I won.
- (Julia) What?

142
00:06:54,740 --> 00:06:56,260
Well done.

143
00:06:56,900 --> 00:06:58,540
Come on, Mr... uh...

144
00:07:21,180 --> 00:07:23,020
all an actress like Julia needs

145
00:07:23,500 --> 00:07:24,300
is a vehicle.

146
00:07:24,500 --> 00:07:26,420
It's the actors the public go to see,

147
00:07:26,580 --> 00:07:27,140
not the play.

148
00:07:27,140 --> 00:07:29,260
That's true in my case. I'd see
you in anything, miss Lambert.

149
00:07:29,460 --> 00:07:31,660
But you know what I'd
really like to find out?

150
00:07:32,100 --> 00:07:32,860
How did you start?

151
00:07:33,060 --> 00:07:34,100
How did you get to be where you are,

152
00:07:34,300 --> 00:07:35,660
owning a theatre, top of the tree?

153
00:07:35,860 --> 00:07:36,860
Clean living and hard work. Cigarette?

154
00:07:37,060 --> 00:07:39,940
We owe it all to a rude, foul-mouthed
brute called Jimmie Langton.

155
00:07:40,580 --> 00:07:42,260
We were in his repertory
company in Middlesbrough.

156
00:07:42,460 --> 00:07:44,900
He knew all there is to know
about theatre and acting.

157
00:07:45,220 --> 00:07:47,220
That's where I met Michael.
That's how we began.

158
00:07:47,860 --> 00:07:49,340
I was a rotten actor.

159
00:07:49,540 --> 00:07:50,860
Yes, but you have presence.

160
00:07:51,060 --> 00:07:53,220
The audience always
gasps when you come on.

161
00:07:53,820 --> 00:07:56,020
It's his dazzling good looks, you see.

162
00:07:56,740 --> 00:07:58,820
Gee, this is fascinating. fascinating.

163
00:07:59,540 --> 00:08:00,100
Dreadfully jealous of him?

164
00:08:00,300 --> 00:08:01,700
You're very sweet, but
I know perfectly well

165
00:08:01,900 --> 00:08:04,140
that all I can play are
diplomats, lawyers and politicians.

166
00:08:04,300 --> 00:08:06,380
I'm more interested in
the business side. that's--

167
00:08:06,580 --> 00:08:07,820
Yes, but you know as well as I do

168
00:08:07,980 --> 00:08:09,700
that we'd be nothing without Jimmie.

169
00:08:09,900 --> 00:08:12,020
I always lay a place
for him at the table.

170
00:08:12,220 --> 00:08:13,340
Just in case he turns up.

171
00:08:13,540 --> 00:08:14,540
He's been dead for 15 years.

172
00:08:14,740 --> 00:08:16,460
Yes, but you never know.

173
00:08:17,260 --> 00:08:18,900
He was a monster.

174
00:08:20,260 --> 00:08:22,180
Uh, how do you spell your first name?

175
00:08:24,060 --> 00:08:25,300
T- O-M.

176
00:08:27,940 --> 00:08:29,260
[Laughing]

177
00:08:30,380 --> 00:08:31,780
[Nib squeaking]

178
00:08:34,540 --> 00:08:36,140
[Gramophone playing]

179
00:08:37,100 --> 00:08:38,700
[People clapping]

180
00:08:39,820 --> 00:08:41,260
[Car honking]

181
00:08:41,940 --> 00:08:43,460
(Dancer) Hoy!

182
00:08:43,780 --> 00:08:44,980
Hoy!

183
00:08:45,180 --> 00:08:46,500
Hoy!

184
00:08:46,940 --> 00:08:47,820
Hoy!

185
00:08:48,020 --> 00:08:49,020
Hoy!

186
00:08:49,220 --> 00:08:50,020
(Archie) For God's sake,

187
00:08:50,220 --> 00:08:52,220
don't torture yourself like this, Laura.

188
00:08:52,980 --> 00:08:54,380
[Julia sobbing]

189
00:08:56,180 --> 00:08:58,220
No one will ever know
how much I loved him.

190
00:09:01,100 --> 00:09:02,780
He was my earth, my moon,

191
00:09:05,140 --> 00:09:07,260
all the stars in the firmament.

192
00:09:16,540 --> 00:09:18,020
Farewell, my love.

193
00:09:21,100 --> 00:09:22,660
[Audience applauding]

194
00:09:25,620 --> 00:09:27,100
Bravo! Bravo!

195
00:09:27,820 --> 00:09:29,460
[People laughing]

196
00:09:41,180 --> 00:09:43,060
No, there's nothing left for me now

197
00:09:43,300 --> 00:09:45,220
but to tour Canada and Australia,

198
00:09:45,420 --> 00:09:46,780
God help me.

199
00:09:47,180 --> 00:09:48,900
Nonsense, miss Lambert.

200
00:09:49,060 --> 00:09:50,220
It's not nonsense.

201
00:09:50,420 --> 00:09:50,980
[Sighing]

202
00:09:51,140 --> 00:09:53,100
I've decided to retire
and let myself go.

203
00:09:54,020 --> 00:09:56,460
I'll have potatoes for lunch
and potatoes for dinner.

204
00:09:59,900 --> 00:10:01,460
Beer. God, I love beer!

205
00:10:03,020 --> 00:10:05,100
And treacle pudding and
cherry tart and cream.

206
00:10:06,100 --> 00:10:08,140
Cream, cream, cream, cream, cream...

207
00:10:08,340 --> 00:10:09,300
[Breathing deeply]

208
00:10:09,460 --> 00:10:10,220
as God is my judge,

209
00:10:10,420 --> 00:10:12,220
I'll never eat a lettuce leaf again.

210
00:10:12,420 --> 00:10:13,260
[Doorbell ringing]

211
00:10:13,460 --> 00:10:15,500
Oh, God, I bet I know who that is.

212
00:10:18,020 --> 00:10:19,620
Good afternoon, Evie.

213
00:10:20,700 --> 00:10:22,580
Oh, Mrs. De Vries, what a surprise.

214
00:10:23,140 --> 00:10:24,900
Uh, I hope this isn't inconvenient

215
00:10:25,380 --> 00:10:27,020
but I have to see miss Lambert

216
00:10:27,220 --> 00:10:28,220
on a business matter.

217
00:10:28,380 --> 00:10:30,420
She isn't having one
of her afternoon naps,

218
00:10:31,100 --> 00:10:32,540
is she?

219
00:10:34,740 --> 00:10:36,020
Wait a minute.

220
00:10:36,220 --> 00:10:37,620
[Door squeaking]

221
00:10:38,420 --> 00:10:39,660
Guess who's here.

222
00:10:39,860 --> 00:10:40,540
Show her in.

223
00:10:40,740 --> 00:10:42,380
Business, she says, but isn't it funny

224
00:10:42,580 --> 00:10:44,140
how she always manages
to time her visits

225
00:10:44,300 --> 00:10:45,900
when you're lying stark bollock naked.

226
00:10:46,100 --> 00:10:48,300
Enough of that, you dirty-minded slut.

227
00:10:49,460 --> 00:10:50,980
Show her in.

228
00:10:53,140 --> 00:10:53,980
Mrs. De Vries.

229
00:10:54,180 --> 00:10:55,060
(Dolly) Julia, darling.

230
00:10:55,260 --> 00:10:56,820
Dolly, dear. hmm.

231
00:10:57,860 --> 00:10:58,780
Oh, I'm so sorry.

232
00:10:58,940 --> 00:11:01,380
I always seem to call when
you're-- you're otherwise engaged.

233
00:11:02,540 --> 00:11:03,260
[Laughing]

234
00:11:03,460 --> 00:11:04,420
- Tea?
- Lovely.

235
00:11:04,620 --> 00:11:06,740
Ignore me. I'll-- I'll just
sit here quiet as a lamb

236
00:11:08,340 --> 00:11:09,820
until you're done.

237
00:11:10,940 --> 00:11:11,580
So Evie said

238
00:11:11,780 --> 00:11:13,740
something about business. Hmm?

239
00:11:16,060 --> 00:11:16,900
What? Oh, yes.

240
00:11:17,100 --> 00:11:19,340
Um, Michael tells me you
want to close the play.

241
00:11:20,140 --> 00:11:22,020
My husband's a devious little runt.

242
00:11:23,380 --> 00:11:24,740
Oh, that's unfair.

243
00:11:24,940 --> 00:11:26,860
He was perfectly right to consult me.

244
00:11:27,060 --> 00:11:28,860
We're partners. the 3 of us.

245
00:11:29,340 --> 00:11:30,500
A perfect combination.

246
00:11:30,700 --> 00:11:32,500
My money, his know-how, your genius.

247
00:11:33,540 --> 00:11:35,100
I'm exhausted, Dolly.

248
00:11:35,260 --> 00:11:35,660
[Grunts]

249
00:11:35,660 --> 00:11:37,700
I feel twice my age which makes me 90.

250
00:11:37,900 --> 00:11:40,180
I'm bored. Life has
nothing in store for me.

251
00:11:40,500 --> 00:11:41,980
You mean that, or are you acting?

252
00:11:42,180 --> 00:11:43,940
I never know when you're acting.

253
00:11:44,140 --> 00:11:45,340
I'm not acting.

254
00:11:45,540 --> 00:11:46,380
I'm near to having a breakdown.

255
00:11:46,580 --> 00:11:48,740
I feel as though my
life's come to an end.

256
00:11:49,140 --> 00:11:50,700
All right. All right.

257
00:11:51,180 --> 00:11:52,260
All done.

258
00:11:52,460 --> 00:11:54,220
Oh, thank you, you're a dear.

259
00:11:56,180 --> 00:11:57,540
Uh.

260
00:11:58,220 --> 00:12:00,180
Are you really near a breakdown, Julia?

261
00:12:01,500 --> 00:12:03,220
Oh, I don't know. I don't know.

262
00:12:05,180 --> 00:12:07,420
I'm in such an odd state at the moment.

263
00:12:07,860 --> 00:12:08,580
[Inhaling]

264
00:12:08,780 --> 00:12:09,340
It's as if...

265
00:12:09,500 --> 00:12:11,820
It's as if the curtain's
come down on act 1,

266
00:12:12,980 --> 00:12:14,940
but I have no idea
what happens in act 2.

267
00:12:15,700 --> 00:12:16,340
[Inaudible mimicking]

268
00:12:16,540 --> 00:12:17,900
