00:25:33,860 --> 00:25:35,700
Debrett's? No, the tatler.

569
00:25:36,020 --> 00:25:36,500
[Laughing]

570
00:25:36,500 --> 00:25:38,620
Oh, you have to know who's
who to get on in this town.

571
00:25:38,820 --> 00:25:40,660
Oh, you want to get on, do you?

572
00:25:40,940 --> 00:25:42,860
I want to get on you, Julia.

573
00:25:43,140 --> 00:25:44,660
Don't be disgusting.

574
00:25:44,860 --> 00:25:46,260
But I want you.

575
00:25:47,780 --> 00:25:49,140
I do.

576
00:25:49,340 --> 00:25:50,180
[Glasses clinking]

577
00:25:50,380 --> 00:25:52,500
You're the loveliest girl that one

578
00:25:55,180 --> 00:25:56,300
I want you.

579
00:25:56,500 --> 00:25:57,300
[Giggling]

580
00:25:57,500 --> 00:25:59,700
Your conversation's
frightfully limited, Tom.

581
00:26:01,260 --> 00:26:02,140
Dance with me.

582
00:26:02,340 --> 00:26:03,940
What time is it?

583
00:26:04,620 --> 00:26:06,700
Oh, well, uh, I... I
forgot to put on my watch.

584
00:26:08,820 --> 00:26:10,300
Have you pawned it?

585
00:26:11,260 --> 00:26:12,620
No, no, I just, uh,

586
00:26:12,820 --> 00:26:14,780
I-- I dressed in
rather a hurry tonight.

587
00:26:16,620 --> 00:26:18,340
# They'll never believe me

588
00:26:20,900 --> 00:26:22,700
# they'll never believe me

589
00:26:25,020 --> 00:26:27,260
# that from this great big world

590
00:26:29,100 --> 00:26:30,780
# you've chosen me... #

591
00:26:32,100 --> 00:26:33,500
[Laughing]

592
00:26:38,420 --> 00:26:40,060
[Julia screaming]

593
00:26:41,700 --> 00:26:43,300
[Continues laughing]

594
00:26:45,900 --> 00:26:47,660
He treated you like a tart.

595
00:26:48,180 --> 00:26:50,060
Which of course is what you are.

596
00:26:52,420 --> 00:26:54,460
(Julia) He was my earth, my moon,

597
00:26:57,500 --> 00:26:59,660
and all the stars in the firmament.

598
00:27:06,140 --> 00:27:08,500
[Whispering] The photo's
in the wrong place!

599
00:27:12,980 --> 00:27:14,460
Farewell, my love.

600
00:27:24,100 --> 00:27:25,940
You were wonderful tonight, my darling.

601
00:27:27,060 --> 00:27:27,780
[Whooping]

602
00:27:27,980 --> 00:27:29,180
Bloody marvelous.

603
00:27:29,380 --> 00:27:30,940
You almost made me cry.

604
00:27:31,500 --> 00:27:32,500
Only almost?

605
00:27:32,700 --> 00:27:34,500
I'll kill whoever set the photo.

606
00:27:34,700 --> 00:27:35,260
Thanks, Archie.

607
00:27:35,260 --> 00:27:36,980
And what've you done to your eyes?

608
00:27:37,180 --> 00:27:38,380
Hmm? Some new makeup?

609
00:27:38,580 --> 00:27:40,500
I've never seen them
shine like that before.

610
00:27:40,980 --> 00:27:42,260
Your call, Mr. Dexter.

611
00:27:42,460 --> 00:27:43,060
Hmm.

612
00:27:43,180 --> 00:27:43,860
[Archie laughing]

613
00:27:44,020 --> 00:27:46,060
Sorry about the photo,
it won't happen again.

614
00:27:47,020 --> 00:27:47,820
Hmm.

615
00:27:48,020 --> 00:27:49,540
Your call, miss Lambert.

616
00:27:49,740 --> 00:27:51,340
You're forgiven.

617
00:27:51,540 --> 00:27:53,100
[Audience applauding]

618
00:27:55,100 --> 00:27:56,740
What's the matter with her?

619
00:27:57,660 --> 00:27:58,780
[Julia exclaiming]

620
00:27:58,980 --> 00:28:00,500
Darling, Julia.

621
00:28:03,100 --> 00:28:04,940
You were quite wonderful tonight.

622
00:28:05,140 --> 00:28:06,780
I'll say. Absolutely first-rate.

623
00:28:06,940 --> 00:28:07,820
Thank you.

624
00:28:08,020 --> 00:28:10,300
Yes, I believe I was
firing on all cylinders.

625
00:28:10,580 --> 00:28:12,820
And I'm starving, absolutely ravenous.

626
00:28:13,460 --> 00:28:15,460
Evie, what have we
got for supper tonight?

627
00:28:15,820 --> 00:28:16,380
Tripe and onions.

628
00:28:16,500 --> 00:28:18,620
Oh, how divine. I
adore tripe and onions.

629
00:28:20,140 --> 00:28:22,140
Michael, Michael, if you love me,

630
00:28:22,340 --> 00:28:24,140
if you've got any spark of tenderness

631
00:28:24,740 --> 00:28:26,060
in that hard heart of yours,

632
00:28:26,260 --> 00:28:28,100
let me have a bottle of beer.

633
00:28:28,340 --> 00:28:28,940
Beer? Yes.

634
00:28:29,140 --> 00:28:30,660
Julia. Just this once.

635
00:28:30,820 --> 00:28:32,540
Oh, Evie, that's for you.

636
00:28:32,780 --> 00:28:33,620
Uh, please?

637
00:28:33,820 --> 00:28:35,660
Julia, I think it's a damn shame.

638
00:28:36,020 --> 00:28:36,660
(Julia) What is?

639
00:28:36,860 --> 00:28:39,060
Well, that you're taking the play off.

640
00:28:39,380 --> 00:28:40,060
The good news is,

641
00:28:40,260 --> 00:28:41,220
I've found an Italian company

642
00:28:41,420 --> 00:28:43,020
who wants the theatre for 3 months,

643
00:28:43,220 --> 00:28:45,260
so I said they could have it. Hmm. Mmm.

644
00:28:45,460 --> 00:28:47,420
I'm sure your mother's
as excited as I am

645
00:28:47,700 --> 00:28:48,980
at the thought of being with you.

646
00:28:49,180 --> 00:28:51,020
We'll have such fun at my place, Julia.

647
00:28:51,220 --> 00:28:53,100
You could do anything you like.

648
00:28:53,300 --> 00:28:54,220
Rest. anything.

649
00:28:54,420 --> 00:28:56,100
I've changed my mind. I don't know why,

650
00:28:56,300 --> 00:28:58,660
but I'm beginning to enjoy
myself again. oh, but--

651
00:28:59,140 --> 00:29:00,260
let's run through the summer

652
00:29:00,420 --> 00:29:02,340
and then find something
new for the autumn.

653
00:29:02,580 --> 00:29:04,540
But I've... I-I've...
I've told the Italians.

654
00:29:05,180 --> 00:29:06,180
Then un-tell them.

655
00:29:06,380 --> 00:29:08,340
And I was so looking forward to France.

656
00:29:09,100 --> 00:29:10,780
Stars will be stars.

657
00:29:15,340 --> 00:29:16,580
I forgot.

658
00:29:16,780 --> 00:29:17,660
What?

659
00:29:17,860 --> 00:29:19,300
Hmm...

660
00:29:22,820 --> 00:29:24,180
[Exclaims]

661
00:29:31,860 --> 00:29:33,420
Oh, my God. A cartier.

662
00:29:34,100 --> 00:29:36,020
Well spotted. When's your birthday?

663
00:29:36,820 --> 00:29:37,740
November 20.

664
00:29:37,940 --> 00:29:38,740
Hmm.

665
00:29:38,940 --> 00:29:39,500
Happy birthday.

666
00:29:39,500 --> 00:29:41,180
Uh, but it's not November 20.

667
00:29:41,340 --> 00:29:43,180
Don't be so pedantic. Open it.

668
00:29:46,060 --> 00:29:48,180
Oh, that's the one thing
I've wanted my whole life.

669
00:29:49,220 --> 00:29:50,100
Thank you.

670
00:29:50,300 --> 00:29:51,820
[Giggles]

671
00:29:52,300 --> 00:29:53,020
Uh, geez, it's lousy

672
00:29:53,220 --> 00:29:55,260
I can't give you anything in return.

673
00:29:55,580 --> 00:29:57,660
Give me that watch you
pawned to buy me supper.

674
00:29:58,260 --> 00:30:00,220
Have you redeemed it yet? Ah! thanks.

675
00:30:04,180 --> 00:30:05,940
It'll amuse me to wear it.

676
00:30:06,460 --> 00:30:07,940
I love you, Julia.

677
00:30:13,020 --> 00:30:13,580
[Sighing]

678
00:30:13,620 --> 00:30:15,740
This is total insanity.
I'm old enough to be...

679
00:30:18,260 --> 00:30:19,660
[Laughing]

680
00:30:20,700 --> 00:30:22,180
God, I'm a fool,

681
00:30:23,340 --> 00:30:24,940
I'm such a bloody fool.

682
00:30:30,220 --> 00:30:31,980
Good morning, Evie. where's my wife?

683
00:30:32,620 --> 00:30:33,540
In your study.

684
00:30:33,740 --> 00:30:35,540
- My study?
- Mmm-hmm.

685
00:30:36,140 --> 00:30:37,620
What's she doing there?

686
00:30:37,820 --> 00:30:39,300
Exercising.

687
00:30:41,340 --> 00:30:42,860
Exercising?

688
00:30:43,740 --> 00:30:45,060
[Grunting]

689
00:30:45,260 --> 00:30:45,820
What are you doing?

690
00:30:46,020 --> 00:30:48,180
Swimming the channel, what
do you think I'm doing?

691
00:30:50,380 --> 00:30:51,620
Yeah, but why?

692
00:30:51,820 --> 00:30:52,300
[Panting]

693
00:30:52,300 --> 00:30:54,380
Miss Phillips said my
tummy needed tightening,

694
00:30:55,780 --> 00:30:57,340
So I'm tightening it.

695
00:30:58,780 --> 00:31:00,300
[Grunting]

696
00:31:01,340 --> 00:31:02,660
Oh.

697
00:31:02,860 --> 00:31:03,300
[Grunting]

698
00:31:03,300 --> 00:31:05,260
Oh, yes, I had a thought.

699
00:31:05,580 --> 00:31:07,020
We should take a country house

700
00:31:07,220 --> 00:31:08,260
for the summer.

701
00:31:08,420 --> 00:31:10,060
What do you think?

702
00:31:10,660 --> 00:31:12,060
[Julia grunting]

703
00:31:15,340 --> 00:31:16,300
I'll talk to you later.

704
00:31:16,500 --> 00:31:17,060
[Continues grunting]

705
00:31:17,140 --> 00:31:19,820
(Michael) So do you think a house
for the summer's a good idea?

706
00:31:20,860 --> 00:31:21,780
Yes.

707
00:31:21,940 --> 00:31:22,540
Golf, swimming, tennis.

708
00:31:22,580 --> 00:31:24,340
It'll be especially good
for Roger. He loves golf.

709
00:31:24,540 --> 00:31:27,140
Then he'll have to decide
what's he gonna do with his life.

710
00:31:27,380 --> 00:31:29,220
I think he should go to university.

711
00:31:29,420 --> 00:31:31,460
He doesn't want to,
and we shouldn't insist.

712
00:31:32,220 --> 00:31:33,660
It's his life.

713
00:31:33,980 --> 00:31:35,540
Oh, yes, I had another idea.

714
00:31:35,740 --> 00:31:38,100
You remember that young
chap I introduced you to?

715
00:31:39,020 --> 00:31:39,620
Which young chap?

716
00:31:39,780 --> 00:31:41,900
That American good-looking fellow.

717
00:31:42,100 --> 00:31:42,660
Remember?

718
00:31:42,860 --> 00:31:44,140
[Clearing throat] No.

719
00:31:44,340 --> 00:31:46,020
He wants to learn the business.

720
00:31:46,220 --> 00:31:47,420
Tom Fennel's his name.

721
00:31:47,580 --> 00:31:49,380
American, you must remember.

722
00:31:50,100 --> 00:31:50,860
Vaguely.

723
00:31:51,060 --> 00:31:52,900
Well, he's frightfully good at his job.

724
00:31:53,340 --> 00:31:54,180
He's a wizard with money.

725
00:31:54,380 --> 00:31:56,340
Lots of American ideas for avoiding tax.

726
00:31:58,540 --> 00:31:59,500
What about him?

727
00:31:59,700 --> 00:32:01,060
Well, I thought we might invite him down

728
00:32:01,260 --> 00:32:03,700
for a couple of weeks to
spend his holiday with us.

729
00:32:05,100 --> 00:32:06,340
Why would we want to do that?

730
00:32:06,540 --> 00:32:08,540
He'll be company for Roger.

731
00:32:08,940 --> 00:32:09,980
He's only a bit older.

732
00:32:10,180 --> 00:32:12,340
Roger will like him, I'm sure of it.

733
00:32:13,300 --> 00:32:14,700
Shall I ask him?

734
00:32:14,940 --> 00:32:16,260
Hmm.

735
00:32:16,900 --> 00:32:18,100
Ah!

736
00:32:18,740 --> 00:32:20,700
(Julia) Remind me to keep exercising.

737
00:32:23,460 --> 00:32:25,220
So, will you come and stay?

738
00:32:25,420 --> 00:32:27,540
Michael says the house is
frightfully comfortable.

739
00:32:28,260 --> 00:32:29,020
Probably not.

740
00:32:29,220 --> 00:32:31,060
I'm going abroad for a couple of months.

741
00:32:31,700 --> 00:32:32,300
(Julia) What fun.

742
00:32:32,500 --> 00:32:34,020
Well, you'll be busy, won't you?

743
00:32:34,220 --> 00:32:36,060
Looking for a new play, reading scripts.

744
00:32:37,420 --> 00:32:39,020
So, what do you think?

745
00:32:39,620 --> 00:32:41,540
He hasn't done justice to your eyes.

746
00:32:42,980 --> 00:32:43,780
As a matter of fact,

747
00:32:43,940 --> 00:32:45,540
there is a play that interests me.

748
00:32:45,740 --> 00:32:46,420
It's about an older woman

749
00:32:46,620 --> 00:32:48,580
who has an affair with a younger man.

750
00:32:48,980 --> 00:32:50,300
Oh, a farce.

751
00:32:50,500 --> 00:32:51,660
Why do you say that?

752
00:32:51,860 --> 00:32:53,980
Well, because everyone
laughs at the older woman.

753
00:32:54,580 --> 00:32:56,540
No, not in this play. It's all serious.

754
00:32:58,580 --> 00:33:00,220
The act 1 curtain's good.

755
00:33:00,940 --> 00:33:02,580
It comes as a shock to her.

756
00:33:02,780 --> 00:33:03,380
What does?

757
00:33:03,460 --> 00:33:05,460
That she's fallen in love with the boy.

758
00:33:06,620 --> 00:33:08,140
And it happens just when everything

759
00:33:08,340 --> 00:33:10,300
seemed to her so dull and unpromising,

760
00:33:10,700 --> 00:33:12,300
as if her life was over.

761
00:33:12,580 --> 00:33:14,460
She finds the affair exhilarating.

762
00:33:15,340 --> 00:33:16,740
And everyone keeps telling her

763
00:33:16,940 --> 00:33:18,620
she looks 10 years younger.

764
00:33:19,020 --> 00:33:20,300
I trust she doesn't confess to the boy

765
00:33:20,500 --> 00:33:22,740
that she loves him. That's always fatal.

766
00:33:23,860 --> 00:33:25,100
Does it sound like something for me?

767
00:33:25,300 --> 00:33:27,380
Oh, don't be ridiculous, Julia.

768
00:33:28,580 --> 00:33:30,740
No, your public would
never stand for it.

769
00:33:31,020 --> 00:33:31,780
If such a woman asked me,

770
00:33:31,980 --> 00:33:33,180
I know what advice I'd give her.

771
00:33:33,380 --> 00:33:34,580
- What?
- Break it off at once.

772
00:33:34,780 --> 00:33:35,860
It will only end in tears.

773
00:33:36,060 --> 00:33:37,620
But, Charles, she can't do that.

774
00:33:37,820 --> 00:33:38,380
Why ever not?

775
00:33:38,380 --> 00:33:40,260
Because she's fallen in love with him,

776
00:33:40,460 --> 00:33:42,100
That's why. She's helpless.

777
00:33:42,380 --> 00:33:43,700
Hmm.

778
00:33:45,460 --> 00:33:47,100
The character in the play.

779
00:33:56,740 --> 00:33:58,220
[Door opens]

780
00:33:58,540 --> 00:34:00,060
Dolly, old thing,

781
00:34:00,780 --> 00:34:01,980
how are you?

782
00:34:02,180 --> 00:34:04,100
I haven't seen you for ages.

783
00:34:06,020 --> 00:34:07,860
Sit down and make yourself, uh,

784
00:34:10,380 --> 00:34:11,340
comfy.

785
00:34:11,540 --> 00:34:13,860
So, come to see that
the old firm's raking in

786
00:34:14,860 --> 00:34:15,460
the dividends for you?

787
00:34:15,620 --> 00:34:17,540
Michael, I'll come
straight to the point.

788
00:34:17,740 --> 00:34:19,060
You know I'm not one to gossip,

789
00:34:19,260 --> 00:34:21,300
but-- but I'm
upset about Julia.

790
00:34:21,500 --> 00:34:22,060
[Sighing]

791
00:34:22,100 --> 00:34:24,700
I think you ought to know that
people are beginning to talk.

792
00:34:24,900 --> 00:34:25,620
What the devil do you mean?

793
00:34:25,820 --> 00:34:27,700
Well, it's absurd that at her age,

794
00:34:28,100 --> 00:34:29,860
she should make herself so conspicuous

795
00:34:30,060 --> 00:34:31,620
with a young boy.

796
00:34:32,180 --> 00:34:34,460
Oh, you mean Tom Fennel?
don't be such a fool, Dolly.

797
00:34:35,580 --> 00:34:36,180
I'm not a fool.

798
00:34:36,380 --> 00:34:38,220
When someone is as well-known as Julia

799
00:34:38,420 --> 00:34:40,700
and they're always seen with the
same man, naturally people talk.

800
00:34:41,580 --> 00:34:43,180
Tom Fennel is a very
good type of American.

801
00:34:43,380 --> 00:34:45,660
He's clean, honest and by
way of being a gentleman.

802
00:34:45,860 --> 00:34:47,940
He's boring, dull, common and a snob.

803
00:34:49,140 --> 00:34:51,260
He's just using Julia.
He's a little gold digger.

804
00:34:53,340 --> 00:34:55,340
Can you look me in the eyes, Dolly,

805
00:34:55,540 --> 00:34:56,380
and tell me you really think

806
00:34:56,580 --> 00:34:58,460
Julia's having an affair with him?

807
00:35:00,300 --> 00:35:01,220
No.

808
00:35:01,420 --> 00:35:01,860
Ah.

809
