01:12:22,460 --> 01:12:26,020
"I asked if he would give
me a letter to the bank.

1583
01:12:26,740 --> 01:12:28,900
"He lifted the towel.

1584
01:12:28,900 --> 01:12:32,340
"His nose was bright red
and his eyes were streaming.

1585
01:12:32,620 --> 01:12:34,980
"He looked awful. He said:

1586
01:12:34,980 --> 01:12:38,500
[Nasalized] 'I'm afraid I
have a nasty cold in my nose.'"

1587
01:12:40,620 --> 01:12:43,020
[All laughing]

1588
01:12:43,020 --> 01:12:45,900
Good.

1589
01:12:47,700 --> 01:12:49,540
"I hope you didn't catch it from him.

1590
01:12:49,540 --> 01:12:52,580
you can't afford a cold
with so much to do."

1591
01:12:52,580 --> 01:12:53,620
Go on.

1592
01:12:53,620 --> 01:12:55,740
"Then he sneezed.

1593
01:12:55,740 --> 01:12:59,140
"I don't think I've ever
heard such a sneeze, Millicent.

1594
01:12:59,860 --> 01:13:00,620
[Inaudible miming]

1595
01:13:00,620 --> 01:13:03,980
(Avice) "It began with a
monstrous intake of breath.

1596
01:13:03,980 --> 01:13:06,860
"Wait, wait. I'll show you.

1597
01:13:12,460 --> 01:13:14,900
[Avice inhaling]

1598
01:13:14,900 --> 01:13:17,340
[Avice gasping]

1599
01:13:17,340 --> 01:13:18,740
[Sneezes]

1600
01:13:18,740 --> 01:13:21,620
[All laughing]

1601
01:13:24,420 --> 01:13:25,740
"I said, 'bless you.'

1602
01:13:25,740 --> 01:13:28,020
"And he said, 'I won't say thank you

1603
01:13:28,020 --> 01:13:31,420
[Mimicking] 'as it's meant
to bring misfortune.'"

1604
01:13:33,940 --> 01:13:35,780
"We should have seen through him.

1605
01:13:35,820 --> 01:13:38,340
"Then it would never have happened.

1606
01:13:38,340 --> 01:13:39,220
"But nowadays

1607
01:13:39,220 --> 01:13:41,020
"we're only interested in appearances.

1608
01:13:41,020 --> 01:13:43,780
And he did have the most
beautiful appearance."

1609
01:13:43,780 --> 01:13:47,180
Uh, mumbo-jumbo. Bad
luck to say the last line.

1610
01:13:47,860 --> 01:13:48,380
[All clapping]

1611
01:13:48,380 --> 01:13:52,340
(Michael) Right, well, I think
we should call it a morning.

1612
01:13:52,700 --> 01:13:53,820
All right?

1613
01:13:53,820 --> 01:13:54,740
Couldn't be better.

1614
01:13:54,740 --> 01:13:57,220
Good reading.
Pleased with the company?

1615
01:13:57,220 --> 01:14:00,140
You've cast it splendidly.

1616
01:14:00,300 --> 01:14:01,940
The girl's clever, isn't she?

1617
01:14:01,940 --> 01:14:04,620
Yes, isn't she?

1618
01:14:04,620 --> 01:14:07,660
- Well, give my love to Roger.
- Ta.

1619
01:14:08,260 --> 01:14:09,340
[Door closing]

1620
01:14:09,340 --> 01:14:11,100
I wouldn't say this to your face,

1621
01:14:11,100 --> 01:14:14,060
so I'll say it to your
back. [Mirror squeaking]

1622
01:14:14,060 --> 01:14:16,220
I've missed you.

1623
01:14:16,220 --> 01:14:19,140
And I've missed you, Evie.

1624
01:14:33,620 --> 01:14:35,020
I did the usual things.

1625
01:14:35,020 --> 01:14:38,220
I saw the sights. Worked
hard at my Italian.

1626
01:14:38,940 --> 01:14:40,140
And went to the opera a good deal.

1627
01:14:40,140 --> 01:14:43,700
Have you made up your mind
what you're going to do yet?

1628
01:14:43,700 --> 01:14:44,620
I want to stop living

1629
01:14:44,620 --> 01:14:46,700
in an atmosphere of make-believe.

1630
01:14:46,700 --> 01:14:48,780
That's your world, not mine.

1631
01:14:48,780 --> 01:14:51,140
And it stifles me.

1632
01:14:51,140 --> 01:14:52,540
What do you mean?

1633
01:14:52,540 --> 01:14:53,300
Once, when I was a kid,

1634
01:14:53,300 --> 01:14:56,700
I was standing in the
wings watching you on-stage.

1635
01:14:57,260 --> 01:14:58,940
It must've been a pretty moving scene

1636
01:14:58,940 --> 01:15:00,980
because I couldn't stop blubbing.

1637
01:15:00,980 --> 01:15:02,900
You moved to the side of the stage

1638
01:15:02,900 --> 01:15:03,820
near where I was standing

1639
01:15:03,820 --> 01:15:06,940
and you turned your back on
the audience, and you said,

1640
01:15:06,940 --> 01:15:08,260
in your ordinary voice:

1641
01:15:08,260 --> 01:15:11,180
"What the bloody hell the
electrician thought he was doing

1642
01:15:11,180 --> 01:15:11,900
with the bright lights."

1643
01:15:11,900 --> 01:15:14,900
And then in the same breath,
with a great cry of anguish

1644
01:15:14,900 --> 01:15:17,540
you just went on with the scene.

1645
01:15:17,540 --> 01:15:20,420
That was acting.

1646
01:15:20,860 --> 01:15:21,860
If I-- if I truly felt

1647
01:15:21,860 --> 01:15:24,100
all the emotions I was representing,

1648
01:15:24,100 --> 01:15:25,020
I'd be a wreck.

1649
01:15:25,020 --> 01:15:26,660
You have a performance for everyone.

1650
01:15:26,660 --> 01:15:29,820
For the servants, for
daddy, for everybody.

1651
01:15:30,140 --> 01:15:32,340
And I don't think you really exist.

1652
01:15:32,340 --> 01:15:32,860
Roger!

1653
01:15:32,860 --> 01:15:36,260
Once you told me something.
I don't remember exactly what,

1654
01:15:36,260 --> 01:15:37,140
but the exact same night

1655
01:15:37,140 --> 01:15:39,020
you said the same line on the stage.

1656
01:15:39,020 --> 01:15:42,140
Even the things you say are second hand.

1657
01:15:43,020 --> 01:15:45,900
All I want is for you to be happy.

1658
01:15:45,900 --> 01:15:48,860
You should talk this
over with your father.

1659
01:15:48,860 --> 01:15:51,020
Mmm, daddy's worse than you are.

1660
01:15:51,020 --> 01:15:53,180
But he only acts one part, thank God,

1661
01:15:53,180 --> 01:15:54,820
and that's the
handsomest man in England.

1662
01:15:54,820 --> 01:15:58,100
Then talk it over with
someone of your own age, then.

1663
01:15:58,100 --> 01:15:59,900
Tom, for instance.

1664
01:15:59,900 --> 01:16:00,740
Tom?

1665
01:16:00,740 --> 01:16:02,220
I thought you liked him.

1666
01:16:02,220 --> 01:16:05,100
No, I didn't like him at all.

1667
01:16:08,540 --> 01:16:11,540
You've dropped him, haven't you?

1668
01:16:14,860 --> 01:16:16,980
I...

1669
01:16:16,980 --> 01:16:19,780
I suppose I have, more or less.

1670
01:16:19,780 --> 01:16:22,900
Good. He wasn't worthy of you.

1671
01:16:25,820 --> 01:16:28,860
Roger, do you think I'm getting old?

1672
01:16:33,180 --> 01:16:36,060
No, not you.

1673
01:16:38,460 --> 01:16:41,700
Mmm, Tom's little tart's
in your play, I hear.

1674
01:16:46,380 --> 01:16:49,180
By the way,

1675
01:16:49,180 --> 01:16:52,300
she's having a fling with daddy.

1676
01:16:59,020 --> 01:17:02,140
[Nasalized] "How's
your cousin Millicent?"

1677
01:17:02,140 --> 01:17:03,940
and I said you were well.

1678
01:17:03,940 --> 01:17:06,260
He wanted to
know-- Michael,

1679
01:17:06,260 --> 01:17:07,300
I'm not happy

1680
01:17:07,300 --> 01:17:09,780
sitting beside her on the bench.

1681
01:17:09,780 --> 01:17:11,820
After all, it's miss Crichton's scene,

1682
01:17:11,820 --> 01:17:13,580
I think I'm too dominant here.

1683
01:17:13,580 --> 01:17:16,940
Well, move if you want to, but where?

1684
01:17:16,940 --> 01:17:20,220
There, on the stool, with
my back to the audience.

1685
01:17:20,620 --> 01:17:22,780
All I am is a feed in this scene

1686
01:17:22,780 --> 01:17:23,820
and it-- it
feels wrong

1687
01:17:23,820 --> 01:17:26,180
to be on equal footing
with miss Crichton.

1688
01:17:26,180 --> 01:17:28,260
I don't mind, really, miss Lambert.

1689
01:17:28,260 --> 01:17:28,860
No, no, no, no,

1690
01:17:28,860 --> 01:17:31,540
I'm uncomfortable. It feels ungenerous.

1691
01:17:31,540 --> 01:17:34,860
Michael, what if I'm discovered there

1692
01:17:35,220 --> 01:17:35,980
when the scene starts?

1693
01:17:35,980 --> 01:17:39,220
(Julia) I could sit facing the swing.

1694
01:17:40,180 --> 01:17:41,660
Then I don't have to move.

1695
01:17:41,660 --> 01:17:42,300
I can stay here

1696
01:17:42,300 --> 01:17:43,620
right until miss Crichton's exit.

1697
01:17:43,620 --> 01:17:46,060
(Julia) to thunderous
applause, I've no doubt. Hmm?

1698
01:17:46,060 --> 01:17:48,980
Well, I'm-- I'm quite
happy to try it.

1699
01:17:50,860 --> 01:17:53,420
Go from the top.

1700
01:17:53,420 --> 01:17:54,260
[Singing]

1701
01:17:54,260 --> 01:17:57,380
(Julia) How was your
interview with sir Philip?

1702
01:17:57,380 --> 01:17:59,100
[Laughs]

1703
01:17:59,100 --> 01:18:00,220
Oh!

1704
01:18:00,220 --> 01:18:02,620
It was like a scene out of dickens.

1705
01:18:02,620 --> 01:18:04,220
[Gasps] He had
the most dread--

1706
01:18:04,220 --> 01:18:07,420
You see? It's much better
with me here, isn't it?

1707
01:18:07,420 --> 01:18:08,060
Well, yes, it is,

1708
01:18:08,060 --> 01:18:10,740
as long as you don't mind being
stuck down there for 10 minutes.

1709
01:18:10,740 --> 01:18:14,100
Mind? Why should I mind? I suggested it.

1710
01:18:15,500 --> 01:18:18,380
(Stagehand) Lower. Lower.

1711
01:18:19,820 --> 01:18:21,900
That's right.

1712
01:18:21,900 --> 01:18:24,780
[Singing]

1713
01:18:25,540 --> 01:18:26,660
[Exclaims]

1714
01:18:26,660 --> 01:18:29,380
It was like a scene out of dickens.

1715
01:18:29,380 --> 01:18:30,460
[Gasps]

1716
01:18:30,460 --> 01:18:32,380
He had the most dreadful cold.

1717
01:18:32,380 --> 01:18:33,340
(Avice) So I said,

1718
01:18:33,340 --> 01:18:35,740
"Should I come back another time?

1719
01:18:35,740 --> 01:18:37,220
And he said:

1720
01:18:37,220 --> 01:18:37,620
[Laughs]

1721
01:18:37,620 --> 01:18:40,980
[Nasalized] "No, no, no, no, no, no."

1722
01:18:50,860 --> 01:18:53,060
[All chattering]

1723
01:18:53,060 --> 01:18:53,820
(Michael) Thank you,

1724
01:18:53,820 --> 01:18:56,100
and then give me all
the light you've got.

1725
01:18:56,100 --> 01:18:57,860
Can't do comedy in the dark.

1726
01:18:57,860 --> 01:18:58,860
Dolly, darling.

1727
01:18:58,860 --> 01:19:00,100
(Dolly) How's it all going?

1728
01:19:00,100 --> 01:19:02,540
Splendid. How was--
how was France?

1729
01:19:02,540 --> 01:19:03,500
Splendid. How's Julia?

1730
01:19:03,500 --> 01:19:04,940
Splendid. And the new girl?

1731
01:19:04,940 --> 01:19:07,660
- We're ready, Mr. Gosselyn.
- Thank you, Mr. Turnbull.

1732
01:19:07,660 --> 01:19:08,380
Dolly, have a seat.

1733
01:19:08,380 --> 01:19:10,140
(Turnbull) Thank you, uh, miss Lambert,

1734
01:19:10,140 --> 01:19:13,300
Mr. Dexter, miss Crichton on the stage.

1735
01:19:13,300 --> 01:19:16,180
(Turnbull) Hold the banging.

1736
01:19:16,500 --> 01:19:19,380
(Julia) Michael.

1737
01:19:19,380 --> 01:19:21,420
I say, that's awfully plain, Julia.

1738
01:19:21,420 --> 01:19:23,100
Precisely. But I want it for 2 reasons.

1739
01:19:23,100 --> 01:19:25,780
Firstly, it's awfully
good for the quick change,

1740
01:19:25,780 --> 01:19:26,580
just hooks up the back.

1741
01:19:26,580 --> 01:19:28,660
Second, I simply don't want in any way

1742
01:19:28,660 --> 01:19:31,900
to distract from miss Crichton.

1743
01:19:33,140 --> 01:19:35,420
(Michael) All right. Happy, Archie?

1744
01:19:35,420 --> 01:19:37,340
Trousers need shortening a bit,

1745
01:19:37,340 --> 01:19:38,260
but that's all.

1746
01:19:38,260 --> 01:19:40,700
And miss Crichton?

1747
01:19:40,700 --> 01:19:43,500
I don't think it fits her properly.

1748
01:19:43,500 --> 01:19:45,340
Especially at the waist.

1749
01:19:45,340 --> 01:19:47,620
And she's got such a pretty figure,

1750
01:19:47,620 --> 01:19:50,780
I think it needs to come
in at least half an inch.

1751
01:19:58,820 --> 01:19:59,500
I don't like it.

1752
01:19:59,500 --> 01:20:00,700
Julia's being far too angelic.

1753
01:20:00,700 --> 01:20:02,940
["Bei mir bist du schon" by
Andrews Sisters playing]

1754
01:20:02,940 --> 01:20:05,740
# Of all the boys I've
known, and I've known some

1755
01:20:05,740 --> 01:20:08,420
# until I first met you I was lonesome

1756
01:20:08,420 --> 01:20:09,820
# and when you came in sight, dear

1757
01:20:09,820 --> 01:20:13,500
# my heart grew light and this
old world seemed new to me

1758
01:20:14,180 --> 01:20:16,020
# you're really swell I have to admit

1759
01:20:16,020 --> 01:20:19,620
# you deserve expressions
that really fit you. #

1760
01:20:20,900 --> 01:20:24,220
' "Nowadays" from J. L.'
and the date. Very nice.

1761
01:20:25,820 --> 01:20:28,020
Here's the list. Can
you wrap each separately

1762
01:20:28,020 --> 01:20:29,940
and have them sent round to the theatre

1763
01:20:29,940 --> 01:20:31,540
no later than 5:00 this evening?

1764
01:20:31,540 --> 01:20:32,540
Of course, miss Lambert.

1765
01:20:32,540 --> 01:20:35,700
I'm so looking forward
to seeing the play.

1766
01:20:38,380 --> 01:20:42,020
(Salesman) It will
make a beautiful gift.

1767
01:20:42,180 --> 01:20:45,060
Yeah.

1768
01:20:46,220 --> 01:20:47,980
T- O-M.

1769
01:20:47,980 --> 01:20:49,580
Julia.

1770
01:20:49,580 --> 01:20:51,500
Are you getting engaged to Avice?

1771
01:20:51,500 --> 01:20:54,740
Oh, this. Oh, no. No,
it's a first-night gift.

1772
01:20:55,540 --> 01:20:57,460
She doesn't want to get engaged.

1773
01:20:57,460 --> 01:20:58,260
Wants her freedom.

1774
01:20:58,260 --> 01:21:01,420
Doesn't want anything to
interfere with her career.

1775
01:21:01,420 --> 01:21:03,140
Her what?

1776
01:21:03,180 --> 01:21:05,700
Oh, yes, I-- I
see what you mean.

1777
01:21:05,700 --> 01:21:09,100
I'm going to be there tonight.
Michael's given me a box.

1778
01:21:09,380 --> 01:21:11,820
(Salesman) Will that be all, sir?

1779
01:21:11,820 --> 01:21:14,700
Yes.

1780
01:21:15,740 --> 01:21:17,900
Tom, how about giving me tea?

1781
01:21:17,900 --> 01:21:21,180
At your place. For old times' sake.

1782
01:21:22,900 --> 01:21:25,780
Why not?

1783
01:21:40,620 --> 01:21:43,300
- Give Avice this.
- Hmm?

1784
01:21:43,300 --> 01:21:46,180
It may bring her luck.

1785
01:21:52,860 --> 01:21:55,740
[Door closing]

1786
01:21:56,260 --> 01:21:59,140
[People chattering]

1787
01:21:59,260 --> 01:22:01,420
[Car honking]

1788
01:22:01,420 --> 01:22:05,060
(Chamberlain) I have in my
hand, this piece of paper

1789
01:22:05,180 --> 01:22:08,740
signed by me, Herr
Hitler, and Benito Macaroni

1790
01:22:10,500 --> 01:22:11,500
in Munich.

1791
01:22:11,500 --> 01:22:14,020
It is for peace in our time.

1792
01:22:14,020 --> 01:22:15,940
However, if there is a war,

1793
01:22:15,940 --> 01:22:18,940
then their majesties, the king and queen

1794
01:22:19,380 --> 01:22:21,860
and their 2 lovely daughters,

1795
01:22:21,860 --> 01:22:24,300
Elizabeth and Margaret rose

1796
01:22:24,300 --> 01:22:26,740
and me and the entire cabinet

1797
01:22:26,740 --> 01:22:29,820
will set sail immediately for Canada!

1798
01:22:31,060 --> 01:22:33,900
You will stay here!

1799
01:22:34,340 --> 01:22:35,660
[Laughs]

1800
01:22:35,660 --> 01:22:36,140
Break a leg.

1801
01:22:36,140 --> 01:22:39,300
(Michael) you're going
to be a sensation.

1802
01:22:39,340 --> 01:22:40,580
Terribly sorry.

1803
01:22:40,580 --> 01:22:42,820
[Laughing]

1804
01:22:42,820 --> 01:22:44,060
[All laughing]

1805
01:22:44,060 --> 01:22:44,860
Same from me, Julia.

1806
01:22:44,860 --> 01:22:47,700
And you're coming to the
party tonight, aren't you?

1807
01:22:47,700 --> 01:22:50,060
Of course, wouldn't
miss it. Thank you both.

1808
01:22:50,060 --> 01:22:51,780
Yes, thank you. Thank you.

1809
01:22:51,780 --> 01:22:52,540
Yes.

1810
01:22:52,540 --> 01:22:53,860
You don't have a whisky handy?

1811
01:22:53,860 --> 01:22:56,780
No, no, no, not here. I've
got all that set up in the bar.

1812
01:22:56,780 --> 01:22:57,660
Darling, we'll see you later.

1813
01:22:57,660 --> 01:23:00,500
Dolly, I'll do the other dressing
rooms and I'll see you in the foyer.

1814
01:23:00,500 --> 01:23:03,980
Uh, bring our distinguished
author with you, will you?

1815
01:23:03,980 --> 01:23:05,020
(Dolly) Yes, of course.

1816
01:23:05,020 --> 01:23:06,540
(Gibbs) Are-- are
we leaving?

1817
01:23:06,540 --> 01:23:07,780
Half an hour, miss Lambert.

1818
01:23:07,780 --> 01:23:09,140
[Both exclaiming]

1819
01:23:09,140 --> 01:23:10,980
So-- so-- so sorry.

1820
01:23:10,980 --> 01:23:13,860
[Laughing]

1821
01:23:14,540 --> 01:23:17,500
(Call boy) hello, Mr. Dexter.

1822
01:23:17,500 --> 01:23:18,420
[Knocking on door]

1823
01:23:18,420 --> 01:23:21,460
(Michael) It's me.

1824
01:23:21,780 --> 01:23:22,820
[Door closes]

1825
01:23:22,820 --> 01:23:23,420
[Knocking]

1826
01:23:23,420 --> 01:23:26,140
(Call boy) Half an hour
please, miss Crichton.

1827
01:23:26,140 --> 01:23:29,020
Oh, Michael.

1828
01:23:29,300 --> 01:23:32,060
Thank you for everything, Michael.

1829
01:23:32,060 --> 01:23:33,780
Here's your first-night present.

1830
01:23:33,780 --> 01:23:36,620
I'm putting you under contract.

1831
01:23:36,620 --> 01:23:38,300
[Gasping]

1832
01:23:38,300 --> 01:23:41,180
Michael. here it is.

1833
01:23:42,180 --> 01:23:44,980
Sign on the front.

1834
01:23:44,980 --> 01:23:46,340
Here you are.

1835
01:23:46,340 --> 01:23:49,220
Oh, thank you.

1836
01:23:49,700 --> 01:23:50,820
[People chattering]

1837
01:23:50,820 --> 01:23:53,780
Good evening, Mrs. De Vries.

1838
01:23:54,620 --> 01:23:57,500
[All chattering]

1839
01:24:01,580 --> 01:24:02,900
Good evening, Roger.

1840
01:24:02,900 --> 01:24:05,780
Charles.

1841
01:24:08,220 --> 01:24:10,060
Aunt Dolly.

1842
01:24:10,060 --> 01:24:11,900
Sweetheart, don't call me aunty.

1843
01:24:11,900 --> 01:24:13,380
Um, we should be going in.

1844
01:24:13,380 --> 01:24:14,020
Oh, yes.

1845
01:24:14,020 --> 01:24:16,020
I'm nervous. I'm going to get a drink.

1846
01:24:16,020 --> 01:24:17,500
It's that way. It's that way.

1847
01:24:17,500 --> 01:24:20,540
Join us upstairs. Got your ticket?

1848
01:24:21,420 --> 01:24:24,300
[Audience chattering]

